title: Grateful Dead Live at Sports Arena on 1994-12-19
lineage: Schoeps MK4's > DAT (48khz) > DA-20mkII > Hosa S/PDIF > Delta DiO 2496 > Peak > WAV @44.1k > SHN (No DAE)
description: Picasso Moon, Stagger Lee, Little Red Rooster, Ramble On Rose, Broken Arrow, When I Paint My Masterpiece*, So Many Roads, Easy Answers, Deal Saint Of Circumstance, New Speedway Boogie-> Nobody's Fault But Mine But Mine-> Women Are Smarter-> Drums-> Space-> I Need A Miracle, The Days Between-> Jam-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: Best of the Later Shows This is one of the best of the later day Dead shows before Jerry was too out of it to play a solo.  New Speedway rocks and Nobodys Fault was played so well for a rare gem.  Days Between is still one of Hunter's best lyrics and Jerry just nails it and adds a nice solo too.

FEEL GOOD Probably the finest show of my career. I didn't "get in" to too many shows, but this sticks out as the most "old school show" that i witnessed. It felt like a Radio City Music Hall show must've felt back in '83, Jerry recites "Stagger Lee" without fail, Dark Starish Jam in the middle of Deal, New Speedway>Nobody's was the first ever, and last Nobody's Fault ever. Also, I've been searching high and low since that day for a quality like this one.
Thank you, archive.org.

College try Have to give the boys credit. The 4 night run, while sloppy at times, was pretty good overall. A 1hr 15 min first set was good and a very inspired first hlaf of the second set with the NSB>Nobody's that really flows. Things bog down a bit after post space, but a good effort overall. Listen to Jer's vocals on Saint of Circumstance and you know it was only a matter of time
talking? I was at this show and it was great,but this recording has people talking during the NSB>NFBM.....hard to imagine talking during that but it's really annoying on this recording........

I was there. This was my last show as a touring deadhead. Thanks for the memories everybody! I went out to the Denver shows a week or so before and had just gotten home to Illinois. It was depressing to be sitting in the cold, crummy mid-west while the boys were playing a mere 1500 miles away; so I recruited my old summer tour pal Jay to ride out with me in my old Subaru Brat[the ultimate tour vehicle for 2 people{we once crammed 7} what other car has 4wd, gets 30+mpg, has T-tops, and has a topper so you can sleep in the back?]. We went to the Oakland shows then drove down the coast to L.A. One of our old friends from the mid-west was living in the desert mountains out side of Palm Springs so we stayed at her house between shows. She had a beautiful little cabin all by itself, so you could wake&bake while sitting on a huge boulder in the front yard with all kinds of psychedelic desert plants all around. Paradise basically. During the day off between shows we cruised down to Venice Beach to spend the night gathered around a fire in a 50 gallon drum with some really unique homeless people & deadheads. If you've ever been to Venice you know they have the craziest boardwalk/fair deal with one man bands, the guy that walks on broken Hieniken bottles, And other crazy street performers. Classic Venice Beach. The show itself is pretty solid, if a little boyond. First set is decent, with a great Stagger Lee, and a really spacey Deal closer. The 2nd set is much better, with a way spaced Saint to open, which was rare as an opener. Next up a great Jerry blues combo; New Speedway is a great song and though this version is a little on the sloppy side it was still fun. They jam this straight into a heartfelt Nobodys Fault; Jerry really gets into the lyrics, as if he knows that the downward spiral his life was in at this point was indeed, nobodys fault but his own. Also this is the first tour w/ telepromters. An average Women are Smarter leads into drums. The space on this night is particularly good & long, there's like 10 minutes of solid jamming with the drummers before launching into a smokin' Miracle, one of my favorite versions from any era. Next the highlight of the show; acrystal clear Days Between, THE BEST EVER, this is one of the highest highlights of my dead career[spanning more than 30 shows]. I think it was Vince that said, on a good night this song just pours out, let me tell you, this one pours like Niagara. Also this is the last song Jerry & Hunter wrote together, this alone gives the song added weight; it is also, lyrically, one of their most affecting compositions, and thanks to the telepromter, Jerry nails all the words, very rare for this song. Its also musically profound. If you put all this together with the pristine performance and you have what I think is one of the most poignent moments in the Deads entire career. Lesh calls this song "achingly nostalgic", it definately makes me think of those hearts of summer held in trust, that I personaly have left on shelves collecting dust. WOW, THATS DEEP! Find me a better version & I'll kiss a fat laidies ass. The Lovelight closer was a bit of a letdown after the emotional roller coaster of the Days. This beeing my last show on tour Brokedown is the PERFECT encore. Mama, Mama, many worlds I've come since I first left home.                                             This is a very listenable aud, though with the exeption of the Days Between I wont recomened it for anybody that wasnt there. At least listen to the Days while in a mellow headspace and I promise it wont disapoint.
